data.content:
## What happened

In C# 14, new built-in span conversions cause `array.Contains(num)` to resolve to **`MemoryExtensions.Contains(Span<T>, T)`** instead of `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)`. `Span`-based methods **cannot be represented in expression trees**, so the compiled expression throws at runtime.

## How to fix it

Force the compiler to bind to `Enumerable.Contains` by casting the array to `IEnumerable<int>`:

```csharp
// Option 1: .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 2: explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

The same class of issue affects `array.Reverse()` (now resolves to the in-place `Span` overload returning `void`). Fix identically with `Enumerable.Reverse(array)` or `array.AsEnumerable().Reverse()`.
